1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:20,000
A worrying message can be serious, a joke, or school research. Parents need context without turning an uncertain signal into an accusation. GuardianNode keeps detection local, then helps a parent decide what to ask next.

2
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:40,000
Before Build Week, GuardianNode already had a visible Windows agent, parent-owned backend, local detection, encrypted evidence, dashboard, authentication, and installers. Portions of the earlier web UI were Claude-assisted; the broader platform was built with Codex assistance.

3
00:00:40,000 --> 00:01:05,000
Six resettable judge scenarios contain no real child data. The normal local detector creates and persists this synthetic incident first. Guardian Review never replaces that local path.

4
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:25,000
Guardian Review loads the authorized incident on the server. Deterministic minimization removes names, accounts, contact details, paths, device identifiers, precise locations, and unrelated context.

5
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:45,000
The parent sees the exact outbound JSON and explicitly continues. Live mode uses the server-side OpenAI Responses API with configurable GPT-5.6, no tools, store false, and a strict schema. This recording uses local mock mode.

6
00:01:45,000 --> 00:02:10,000
The result is not presented as fact. It separates observation from inference, surfaces benign explanations and missing context, and suggests calm opening words. Feedback stays local and does not silently change production behavior.

7
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:35,000
Codex helped preserve the baseline, implement and test Guardian Review, build fifty-five synthetic evaluation cases, and run adversarial review. We disabled a coding-agent transport when its local tools proved to be the wrong privacy boundary.

8
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:48,000
GuardianNode keeps the parent in control. It is an alpha second opinion—not a diagnosis, emergency service, punishment engine, or replacement for a trusted family conversation.
